[b]Markov State Engine [WavesUnchained][/b]

[b]What it does[/b]
The Markov State Engine classifies every bar into one of six market states and measures, from history, where similar states resolved when they ended. It is a regime RESOLUTION map, not a price forecast — the percentages describe how comparable past states resolved, not a prediction of this instance. It is a regime/context tool and does not fire a standalone trade trigger; its directional read is a contextual bias.

[b]The six states[/b]
[list]
[*]Expansion / Chaos and Compression (extreme regimes — tested first)
[*]Up Trend / Down Trend (confirmed trend)
[*]Up Weak / Down Weak (directional context without a confirmed trend)
[/list]
Up/down context comes from price vs EMA and EMA slope (normalized by ATR, so it is scale-free across instruments); "trend" combines ADX strength with path efficiency, so ADX measures strength only, never direction. Compression requires both ATR Rank and an independent BB Width Rank to be low. The state is debounced so brief flicker does not pollute the statistics.

[b]Exit-conditional Markov resolution[/b]
A first-order chain on sticky regimes is diagonal-dominant — the most likely "next" state is almost always the current one, which just restates the present. So the model is exit-conditional: self-transitions are excluded and reported separately as Persistence, and the remaining exits are aggregated into Exit → Bull / Bear / Neutral. The read is "when this regime breaks, where did it go?"
[list]
[*]Self-transitions excluded; Persistence shows how sticky the state is
[*]Laplace smoothing keeps thin samples from reading a misleading 0% / 100%
[*]The most likely exit destination is shown explicitly
[*]Compression's historical match is further conditioned on a bullish/bearish/neutral flavor, so its exit history is drawn from analogous squeeze setups rather than any Compression
[/list]

[b]Two axes — timing vs direction[/b]
The key to reading this tool: it has two quality axes that are not equally trustworthy. TIMING (Persistence and Maturity) is computed from every in-state bar and is robust. DIRECTION (the exit distribution and Reliability) hangs on the few times the state actually ended, so on sticky states it is statistically thin — and is flagged as such.
[list]
[*]Maturity = current dwell vs the state's typical dwell (1/(1−Persistence)): Fresh / Mature / Extended / Overdue — a coiled-spring gauge
[*]"Overdue" is descriptive (unusually long vs history), not a claim that an exit is mechanically due
[*]Direction is flagged "below min sample" when built on too few exits
[/list]

[b]Reliability[/b]
A high probability is meaningless on a tiny or near-uniform sample. Reliability combines sample adequacy with directional predictability (one minus the normalized entropy of the Bull/Bear/Neutral distribution). It stays deliberately strict — regime exits are genuinely close to random on most instruments.

[b]Signals[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Bias[/b] — a stable directional state with hysteresis (no per-bar flicker)
[*][b]Edge[/b] — fires when an exit lean clears confidence and reliability, typed by origin state as Reversal, Breakout (out of Compression/Chaos) or Continuation
[*][b]Watch[/b] — a directional lean that is not yet confident/reliable (visual only, off by default)
[/list]

[b]Plot & background[/b]
The Resolution Bias line is a stepline — it only changes value when the state exits, so it holds flat instead of reading as a continuously evolving curve. Line color is gated by actionability: bold green/red only once confidence and reliability both clear their thresholds, muted grey otherwise, so color alone is the verdict. The pane background tints only Compression/Chaos, with intensity scaling by Maturity — a fresh squeeze is barely tinted, an overdue one reads clearly more saturated.

[b]Readout[/b]
In-pane label grouped into Timing / Direction / Quality lines, that lights up only when something is actionable (green/red reliable direction, amber coiled state, grey otherwise): current state, a Timing line (Maturity, ratio, typical dwell), a Direction line (Bull/Bear/Neutral distribution and likely exit destination), and a Quality line (Reliability, exits sampled with a below-min-sample flag, Persistence). The headline only names a Bullish/Bearish Bias once both confidence and reliability clear their thresholds — otherwise it reads "No reliable direction".

